00:00:16.216 --> 00:00:18.557
Now, the first question
is, "What is the difference

00:00:18.557 --> 00:00:21.474
between PTSD dissociation and DID?"

00:00:22.662 --> 00:00:25.601
DID being Dissociative Identity Disorder,

00:00:25.601 --> 00:00:28.601
otherwise known as Multiple
Personality Disorder.

00:00:28.601 --> 00:00:29.434
Just FYI.

00:00:30.325 --> 00:00:35.242
"If you dissociate because of
your PTSD, do you have DID?

00:00:35.242 --> 00:00:36.075
"Thanks."

00:00:36.075 --> 00:00:36.987
Now, that's a great question.

00:00:36.987 --> 00:00:40.320
And the truth of it is that in order to,

00:00:41.748 --> 00:00:44.852
a lot of people with PTSD will dissociate,

00:00:44.852 --> 00:00:48.178
and they do not necessarily have DID,

00:00:48.178 --> 00:00:50.291
Dissociative Identity Disorder.

00:00:50.291 --> 00:00:53.749
Dissociative Identity
Disorder is when you create

00:00:53.749 --> 00:00:55.978
a complete alternate universe that you

00:00:55.978 --> 00:00:59.266
kind of daydream slash live in.

00:00:59.266 --> 00:01:01.855
And people, that's why they
call Multiple Personality,

00:01:01.855 --> 00:01:03.791
because you actually can
create, like, an alter ego

00:01:03.791 --> 00:01:06.438
to some extent and you can
kind of live in that land.

00:01:06.438 --> 00:01:08.876
So, imagine if you're,
you know, day dreaming

00:01:08.876 --> 00:01:11.485
and you're like, you
know, I'm going to live in

00:01:11.485 --> 00:01:13.402
this beautiful house on a hill, and I'll

00:01:13.402 --> 00:01:15.735
have all these dogs or whatever.

00:01:15.735 --> 00:01:18.011
You can create a happier place.

00:01:18.011 --> 00:01:20.008
And this is something that
we do, kind of, as a way

00:01:20.008 --> 00:01:23.642
to cope, which is why it's
linked so much to PTSD.

00:01:23.642 --> 00:01:24.808
The difference being, you can have

00:01:24.808 --> 00:01:29.001
PTSD and dissociate sometimes,
but if it's taking up

00:01:29.001 --> 00:01:33.056
a significant portion of your
time, then it would be DID.

00:01:33.056 --> 00:01:35.439
And you can have PTSD and DID,

00:01:35.439 --> 00:01:37.910
but they don't always happen that way.

00:01:37.910 --> 00:01:38.934
Okay, does that make sense?

00:01:38.934 --> 00:01:41.088
So, sometimes you'll have one with,

00:01:41.088 --> 00:01:43.080
you'll have dissociation with PTSD,

00:01:43.080 --> 00:01:45.484
but only if it's taking up a significant

00:01:45.484 --> 00:01:49.075
portion of time is it actually DID, okay?

00:01:49.075 --> 00:01:50.521
Question number two.

00:01:50.521 --> 00:01:52.293
"Is it normal to just start crying?"

00:01:52.293 --> 00:01:53.790
I've gotten this question,
I think it's from

00:01:53.790 --> 00:01:54.623
the same person that have been

00:01:54.623 --> 00:01:57.116
following me around all week.

00:01:57.116 --> 00:01:58.199
No, it's not.

00:02:00.141 --> 00:02:03.021
Most of the time, if you're
crying for what we would,

00:02:03.021 --> 00:02:04.745
you know, when my clients will say, Kati,

00:02:04.745 --> 00:02:06.738
I'm just crying for no reason,

00:02:06.738 --> 00:02:09.383
there's no real reason, I'm just crying.

00:02:09.383 --> 00:02:11.532
It's usually because
we're really overwhelmed,

00:02:11.532 --> 00:02:13.769
and our anxiety is really
high, or our depression

00:02:13.769 --> 00:02:17.001
is really bad, and the
smallest things or nothing

00:02:17.001 --> 00:02:18.573
really can just set us off, right?

00:02:18.573 --> 00:02:21.756
And then we instantly start crying.

00:02:21.756 --> 00:02:25.755
Because, another thing to think about is

00:02:25.755 --> 00:02:29.574
what we hypothesize as
being the reason for our

00:02:29.574 --> 00:02:32.342
depression and anxiety and stuff like that

00:02:32.342 --> 00:02:36.064
is kind of a, the
neurotransmitters in our brain

00:02:36.064 --> 00:02:38.647
aren't keeping our dopamine and

00:02:39.496 --> 00:02:41.306
serotonin at the right levels.

00:02:41.306 --> 00:02:43.758
That's what they hypothesize, right?

00:02:43.758 --> 00:02:46.826
So, those are very
clearly linked to hormones

00:02:46.826 --> 00:02:49.527
and affects our mood and so things,

00:02:49.527 --> 00:02:51.293
if we're depressed, or if we're anxious,

00:02:51.293 --> 00:02:54.178
or kind of mood and our
hormones and all that stuff

00:02:54.178 --> 00:02:55.537
is going all out of wack, so we might

00:02:55.537 --> 00:02:56.558
just cry for no reason.

00:02:56.558 --> 00:02:59.759
We might want to yell
at someone and then cry,

00:02:59.759 --> 00:03:01.174
or you know, we just kind of feel like

00:03:01.174 --> 00:03:03.405
our emotions aren't under our own control.

00:03:03.405 --> 00:03:05.894
So, if you're feeling like
you're crying all the time

00:03:05.894 --> 00:03:07.918
in places where you don't want to cry,

00:03:07.918 --> 00:03:09.480
and times where you don't want to cry,

00:03:09.480 --> 00:03:10.980
I would encourage you to seek some

00:03:10.980 --> 00:03:12.414
professional help and see a therapist

00:03:12.414 --> 00:03:15.253
because talking it out
can honestly really help.

00:03:15.253 --> 00:03:16.813
